ed": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9950807094573975, "span": {"begin": 764, "end": 768}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1592"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP26 enzymes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9651767015457153, "span": {"begin": 772, "end": 785}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.994459867477417, "span": {"begin": 805, "end": 809}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fetal male germ cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9343348741531372, "span": {"begin": 811, "end": 832}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981693029403687, "span": {"begin": 897, "end": 901}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fetal male germ cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9188268184661865, "span": {"begin": 991, "end": 1012}}, {"id": ["CL:0000670"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "gonocyte", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4452046751976013, "span": {"begin": 1040, "end": 1048}}], "text": "Germs cells undergo meiotic cell division to produce haploid sperm or eggs from diploid gonocytes or oocytes, respectively. Meiotic entry occurs during fetal life in germ cells of ovaries but postnatally in germ cells of testes (Spiller et al, 2017). During late fetal life, germ cells in testes remain in a state of mitotic quiescence and it isn&rsquo;t until prior to puberty that they initiate meiotic entry.   All-trans retinoic acid (atRA) is suggested to induce meiosis in both males and females at the appropriate life stages. atRA prompts germ cells of the developing ovary to initiate first round of meiosis during fetal life, whereas male germ cells in the developing testis is prevented from entering meiosis until puberty by the effective breakdown of atRA by CYP26 enzymes. In the absence of atRA, fetal male germ cells enter cell cycle quiescence (Spiller et al, 2017). If, however, atRA is ectopically expressed in the fetal testis, premature meiotic initiation is induced in fetal male germ cells, which ultimately disrupts gonocyte development.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:35:58 +0000 2026"}